JAMES: Joint Anthropometric Measurement and Evaluation Server

Stef van Buuren

05-06-2019

JAMES

The Joint Anthropometric Measurement and Evaluation Server (JAMES) is an experimental online resource for creating growth charts. The resource can be used by anyone interested in high-quality charts for monitoring and evaluating childhood growth.

This document explains how to set up communications with JAMES and provides some guidance in its use.

Architecture

The growth charts in JAMES are programmed in R. JAMES makes these available through the OpenCPU system for scientific computing and reproducuble research. The system allows for easy integration of growth charts into any HTTP compliant client by means of OpenCPUs API.

Access

JAMES is located at url groeidiagrammen.nl. The sections below use curl for illustration, but any HTTP client will work.

In order to check whether JAMES is running, try generating some random numbers by calling stats::rnorm(), in a terminal window as follows,

curl http://groeidiagrammen.nl/ocpu/library/stats/R/rnorm/json --data n=5
##   % Total    % Received % Xferd  Average Speed   Time    Time     Time  Current
##                                  Dload  Upload   Total   Spent    Left  Speed

Save this file as client3.json on your local system by

curl http://groeidiagrammen.nl/ocpu/library/james/testdata/client3.json -O

which produces a file called client3.json in the work directory.

You may now change its values (but not the file structure), and re-upload it to JAMES. Convert the file from BDS format into an R object of S4 class minihealth::individual as

# NOT YET FUNCTIONAL CURL
curl http://groeidiagrammen.nl/ocpu/library/james/R/convert_bds_ind \
  -d "txt=list(path='client3.json',type='application/json')"

NOTE: The above curl command does not yet work.

A working alternative in R (via the httr package) is as follows. Download the example file to the working directory as

library("httr")
url <- "http://groeidiagrammen.nl/ocpu/library/james/testdata/client3.json"
GET(url, write_disk("client3.json", overwrite = TRUE))
## Response [http://groeidiagrammen.nl/ocpu/library/james/testdata/client3.json]
##   Date: 2019-06-05 16:43
##   Status: 200
##   Content-Type: application/json
##   Size: 2.31 kB
## <ON DISK>  /Users/buurensv/Package/james.client/james.client/Rmd/client3.json

Let us now re-upload and convert the local BDS-formatted file client3.json into the JAMES format (defined as S4 class minihealth::individual) by

url <- "http://groeidiagrammen.nl"
path <- "ocpu/library/james/R/convert_bds_ind"
dat <- upload_file("client3.json")
resp <- POST(url = url, path = path, body = list(txt = dat))
resp
## Response [http://groeidiagrammen.nl/ocpu/library/james/R/convert_bds_ind]
##   Date: 2019-06-05 16:43
##   Status: 201
##   Content-Type: text/plain; charset=utf-8
##   Size: 297 B

The james.client package contains a few utility functions to extract urls for further processing. The following code blocks installs the packages, if not yet available.

if (!"remotes" %in% rownames(installed.packages())) 
  install.packages("remotes")
if (!"james.client" %in% rownames(installed.packages())) 
  remotes::install_github("stefvanbuuren/james.client")

The return value of the server-side function convert_bds_ind() can now be downloaded as

suppressPackageStartupMessages(library("james.client"))
url_ret <- get_url(resp, "return")

Requesting a growth chart

BDS-data as input

The server-side function james::draw_chart_bds() generates a growth chart with the childs BDS-data. It performs three actions: convert the BDS-data into individual data, select a chart based on the input data, and draw the chart.

path <- "ocpu/library/james/R/draw_chart_bds"
resp2 <- POST(url = url, path = path, body = list(txt = dat))
resp2
## Response [http://groeidiagrammen.nl/ocpu/library/james/R/draw_chart_bds]
##   Date: 2019-06-05 16:43
##   Status: 201
##   Content-Type: text/plain; charset=utf-8
##   Size: 300 B
## /ocpu/tmp/x004bc4f14a6d88/R/.val
## /ocpu/tmp/x004bc4f14a6d88/R/draw_chart_bds
## /ocpu/tmp/x004bc4f14a6d88/graphics/1
## /ocpu/tmp/x004bc4f14a6d88/source
## /ocpu/tmp/x004bc4f14a6d88/console
## /ocpu/tmp/x004bc4f14a6d88/info
## /ocpu/tmp/x004bc4f14a6d88/files/client3.json
## /ocpu/tmp/x004bc4f14a6d88/files/DESCRIPTION

The produced height chart for this child can be added to a markdown document as

url_svg <- get_url(resp2, "svg")
url_svg
## [1] "http://groeidiagrammen.nl/ocpu/tmp/x004bc4f14a6d88/graphics/1/svg?width=7&height=7"
tmp <- tempfile(fileext = ".svg")
GET(url_svg, write_disk(tmp))
## Response [http://groeidiagrammen.nl/ocpu/tmp/x004bc4f14a6d88/graphics/1/svg?width=7&height=7]

We may display it in a browser as

browseURL(url_svg)

Data on server as input

The draw_chart_ind() function also draws charts, but takes its input data from a server-side url that contains the already converted individual data. Hence, conversion of the BDS-data need to be done only once. More specifically, draw_chart_ind() loads the individual data stored on the server in a previous call, and return the requested chart. It works as follows:

# request preterm chart with all measures for boys, week 25
path <- "ocpu/library/james/R/draw_chart_ind"
resp3 <- POST(url = url, path = path,
              body = list(location = get_url(resp, "location"),
                          chartcode = "PMAAN25",
                          curve_interpolation = TRUE),
              encode = "json")
resp3
## Response [http://groeidiagrammen.nl/ocpu/library/james/R/draw_chart_ind]
##   Date: 2019-06-05 16:43
##   Status: 201
##   Content-Type: text/plain; charset=utf-8
##   Size: 255 B
## /ocpu/tmp/x0a2457aec25f4f/R/.val
## /ocpu/tmp/x0a2457aec25f4f/R/draw_chart_ind
## /ocpu/tmp/x0a2457aec25f4f/graphics/1
## /ocpu/tmp/x0a2457aec25f4f/source
## /ocpu/tmp/x0a2457aec25f4f/console
## /ocpu/tmp/x0a2457aec25f4f/info
## /ocpu/tmp/x0a2457aec25f4f/files/DESCRIPTION

This growth chart can displayed in the same way as before:

tmp <- tempfile(fileext = ".svg")
url_svg <- get_url(resp3, "svg", pad = "?width=10&height=12")
GET(url_svg, write_disk(tmp))
## Response [http://groeidiagrammen.nl/ocpu/tmp/x0a2457aec25f4f/graphics/1/svg?width=10&height=12]
##   Date: 2019-06-05 16:43
##   Status: 200
##   Content-Type: image/svg+xml
##   Size: 446 kB
## <ON DISK>  /var/folders/py/58s36gjn5kn9zw6rfr7mnx680000gn/T//RtmpuWNLhd/file885d6d52e69a.svg
knitr::include_graphics(tmp)

Note that the reference chart for height has changed (since we asked for week 25 instead of week 27), and the childs measurements are identical.

We can also view it by pasting the url in the browser:

url_svg
## [1] "http://groeidiagrammen.nl/ocpu/tmp/x0a2457aec25f4f/graphics/1/svg?width=10&height=12"

Note that these urls are temporary, and will disappear from the server after 24 hours.

A client in R

If R is your analysis environment, then you can use the james.client package to achieve the same result in an easier way. The functions upload_bds() and request_chart() in james.client have simple syntax, and automate the steps outlined above. See https://github.com/stefvanbuuren/james.client for more detail.

Next steps

The next step is to extend the system so that individual data can be easily plotted and manipulated using a simple app. A first version (one that does not yet use individual plotting, and that uses Dutch growth reference primarily) is on http://groeidiagrammen.nl/ocpu/library/james/www/.
